<span id="freeTextContainer9083135576382940983">On the surface, this is a sensual, reflective, and sometimes humorous recollection of the narratorâ€™s loves won and lost, compared with the current one. Unwelcome news triggers a difficult choice, with huge ramifications. It was made with love, but was it the right decision, and did the narrator even have the right to make it? Itâ€™s a curious amalgam of styles, yet unmistakably Winterson, including a set of short, more abstract sections, and the fact the bisexual narratorâ€™s gender is unspecified.<br/> </span>
  <span id="freeText9083135576382940983" style="display:none">On the surface, this is a sensual, reflective, and sometimes humorous recollection of the narratorâ€™s loves won and lost, compared with the current one. Unwelcome news triggers a difficult choice, with huge ramifications. It was made with love, but was it the right decision, and did the narrator even have the right to make it? Itâ€™s a curious amalgam of styles, yet unmistakably Winterson, including a set of short, more abstract sections, and the fact the bisexual narratorâ€™s gender is unspecified.<br> <br>But peel back the gilt and whatâ€™s beneath is not so straightforward. All the best literature has a unique message for every reader, on each encounter. Gilt reflects: what spoke to me is not what you will hear and respond to. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1554646895i/27328043.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>Antique mirror</i> (<a href="https://homeguides.sfgate.com/identify-antique-mirrors-89891.html" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>.)<br><br>I found this shockingly, painfully good. I knew it was about relationships and was ambiguous about gender, but I was unprepared for the raw dissection of loss. It punched hard, but was shot through with love. Definitely the right book at the right time for me. <br><br>â€œ<i>
  <b>Why is the measure of love loss?</b>
</i>â€<br><br>The opening line, repeated later, brought tears. Itâ€™s the converse of my recent experience of grief as the price of love - love with nowhere to go. But nevertheless, and without question, â€œLove is worth itâ€.<br><br>"<i>You don't get over it because 'it' is the person you loved.</i>"<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1554646895i/27328044._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: My fatherâ€™s keys, his writing instantly recognisable from just four letters.<br>â€œ<i>No-one tells you in grief-counselling or books on loss what it will be like when you find part of the beloved unexpectedly.</i>â€<br><br><b>Love isâ€¦</b><br><br>â€œ<i>I went to churchâ€¦ I wanted the comfort of other peopleâ€™s faith.</i>â€<br><br>The Bible of her childhood infuses atheist Wintersonâ€™s writing, and this is no exception: phrases, ideas, and liturgical repetition and rhythm. Here, itâ€™s most obvious in how the â€œemotional nomadâ€ writes about love:<br><br>â€œ<i>Love demands expression. It will not stay still, stay silent, be good, be modest, be seen and not heard, no.</i>â€<br>and<br>â€œ<i>No-one can legislate love; it cannot be given orders or cajoled into service. Love belongs to itself, deaf to pleading and unmoved by violence. Love is not something you can negotiate. Love is the one thing stronger than desire and the only proper reason to resist temptation.</i>â€<br><br>From 1 Corinthians 13, v4-8 (NIV):<br>â€œ<i>Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud. It does not dishonor others, it is not self-seeking, it is not easily angered, it keeps no record of wrongs. Love does not delight in evil but rejoices with the truth. It always protects, always trusts, always hopes, always perseveres. Love never fails.</i>â€ <br><br>But I donâ€™t think the Bible is right: love <b>can</b> fail:<br>â€œ<i>What then kills love? Only this: neglect.</i>â€<br><br>The other message, from way back in 1992, is that gender doesnâ€™t matter; there is no question or hand-wringing; itâ€™s not relevant to the story. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1554647314i/27328052.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>â€œLove is loveâ€ in current parlance.</i> (<a href="https://www.shutterstock.com/image-vector/gay-love-1101422276" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>.)<br><br><b>Marriage</b><br><br>â€œ<i>Is happiness always a compromise?</i>â€<br>â€œ<i>Contentmentâ€¦ are you sure itâ€™s not an absence of feeling?</i>â€<br><br>In my teens, I remember my father quoting (allegedly) Prince Philip: â€œMarriage is the highest form of prostitutionâ€. There is truth in that, touched on repeatedly here. We all exchange things for sex and love: our motives are mixed and rarely pure. And the promises of marriage can be hard to keep.<br><br>â€œ<i>Marriage is the flimsiest weapon against desire.</i>â€<br>â€œ<i>Cheating is easyâ€¦ To borrow against the trust someone has placed in you costs nothing <b>at first</b>.</i>â€<br><br><b>The Translator, Translated</b><br><br>â€œ<i>Articulacy of the fingersâ€¦ signing on the body body longing.</i>â€<br>â€œ<i>Your flesh is my flesh. You deciphered me and now I am plain to read.</i>â€<br><br>The narrator is a translator (there are many references to great literature, as usual for Winterson), but better in abstract than with those they love, let alone themself.<br><br>â€œ<i>Written on the body is a secret code only visible in certain lightsâ€¦ In places the palimpsest is so heavily worked that the letters feel like Brailleâ€¦ I didnâ€™t know that Louse would have reading hands. She has translated me into her own book.</i>â€<br><br><b>Bio-anatomical Prose Poetry</b><br><br>â€œ<i>I know the stigmata of presumption.</i>â€<br><br>There are no chapters, but two-thirds through, there are four short sections that defy easy description: semi-abstract musings on cells,