put herself first.â€<br>â€¢	â€œHer husband lies over her like a tarpaulin.â€<br>â€¢	â€œThe women wore their jewellery like medalsâ€¦ a palimpsest of love-affairsâ€ on show at the opera.<br>â€¢	 â€œIâ€™d run my hands over her padded flesh with all the enthusiasm of a second-hand sofa dealer.â€<br>â€¢	â€œThey considered themselves to be Australian aristocracy, that is, they were descended from convicts.â€<br>â€¢	â€œShe had a steady hand but she like to spill. It made work for her daughter.â€<br><br>Other<br>â€¢	â€œWhat you risk reveals what you value.â€<br>â€¢	â€œPeople usually know exactly why they are happy. They very rarely know why they are miserable.â€<br><br>Winterson is queen of the extended metaphor. This is one of many (others include maps, animals, jigsaws):<br>â€œ<i>When she lifted the soup spoon to her lips how I longed to be that innocent piece of stainless steelâ€¦ Let me be diced carrot, vermicelli, just so that you will take me in your mouth. I envied the French stick. I watched her break and butter each piece, soak it slowly in her bowl, let it float, grow heavy and fat, sink under the deep red weight and then be resurrected to the glorious pleasure of her teethâ€¦ I will taste you if only through your cooking.</i>â€</span>
