    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1933919942" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1933919942" />
    <a title="El" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83144-el"><img alt="El" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479156984p2/83144.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1933919942?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="El" class="user" itemprop="url" name="El" href="/user/show/83144-el">El</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to El by: </span>
      The F-Word
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83144-el?shelf=20th-centurylit-late">20th-centurylit-late</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83144-el?shelf=1001-books-list">1001-books-list</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83144-el?shelf=hear-me-roar-and-gender">hear-me-roar-and-gender</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1933919942" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6439194698849221022">This is the second book now that I&apos;ve read by Jeanette Winterson and I just want to keep reading her. Her stories are familiar, as in I can recognize that each is written by Winterson, because she has a way with words that not many authors can manage even if they wanted to. It&apos;s distinctly Winterson, and that&apos;s refreshing.<br/><br/>In this book, we have a genderless narrator. What does that mean? The narrator may in fact have a gender, but the point is that we, as the readers, do not have any idea. Is the</span>
  <span id="freeText6439194698849221022" style="display:none">This is the second book now that I've read by Jeanette Winterson and I just want to keep reading her. Her stories are familiar, as in I can recognize that each is written by Winterson, because she has a way with words that not many authors can manage even if they wanted to. It's distinctly Winterson, and that's refreshing.<br /><br />In this book, we have a genderless narrator. What does that mean? The narrator may in fact have a gender, but the point is that we, as the readers, do not have any idea. Is the narrator male or female? Does it matter? And more importantly, <i>why do we care?</i> It's unsettling, still in this day and age, to not know from the start whose story we're reading. As the narrator details their sexual exploits with men and women, we are left still uncertain, and ultimately it doesn't even matter. It's a story of love and devotion, lust, the way our stories are imprinted on our lovers' bodies. I say Winterson was ahead of the curve here with this one, illustrating to readers that our stories are not based on our genders, but on the love we can provide to another and accept in return.<br /><br />It's quite beautiful, really.<br /><br />There's a bit in the middle that reads more like an anatomical guide than a novel, but even that is written in Winterson's exquisite prose.<br /><blockquote>"He made me shave off all my body hair and did the same to himself. He claimed it would increase sensation but it made me feel like a prisoner in a beehive."<br />(p143)</blockquote><br />So far with this book and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15055.Oranges_Are_Not_the_Only_Fruit" title="Oranges Are Not the Only Fruit by Jeanette Winterson" rel="nofollow noopener">Oranges Are Not the Only Fruit</a>, I find myself at a distance from Winterson's writing, even though I have liked it so much both times. It's more an appreciation, but there's an emotional distance I find to her writing, like I can't quite get inside of it, like I'm not ready, perhaps, or it's not meant for me. It's not that I feel excluded; I just find myself trying to reach depths in her writing that I don't think she means to be reached, and as much as I like it, I can't say I <i>love</i> it.<br /><br />But it does keep me coming back for more. That's the magic of her writing and her stories. I may be getting a little addicted to it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6439194698849221022" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

