<div id="review_17854255" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/17854255" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/54697-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1353271036p2/54697.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/17854255?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/54697-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54697-matt?shelf=top-shelf">top-shelf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54697-matt?shelf=shattering">shattering</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54697-matt?shelf=femmes">femmes</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54697-matt?shelf=worldly-lit">worldly-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54697-matt?shelf=fictions-of-the-big-it">fictions-of-the-big-it</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer17854255" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10599111168969980417">Looking over my shelves, I came across this book again and I can&apos;t believe I had rated it only three stars, barely categorized it, and went about my merry way.<br/><br/> No.<br/><br/> I remember reading this in one night, after crashing at a friend&apos;s house, after idly picking it up and suddenly dedicating the next however many hours of the night into the sickly morning to going all the way. All the way in it. Submerged. All the way to the bitter fucking end. <br/><br/> I think I wrote a long, detiled, passionate review of th</span>
  <span id="freeText10599111168969980417" style="display:none">Looking over my shelves, I came across this book again and I can't believe I had rated it only three stars, barely categorized it, and went about my merry way.<br /><br /> No.<br /><br /> I remember reading this in one night, after crashing at a friend's house, after idly picking it up and suddenly dedicating the next however many hours of the night into the sickly morning to going all the way. All the way in it. Submerged. All the way to the bitter fucking end. <br /><br /> I think I wrote a long, detiled, passionate review of this book a long time ago and the computer fucked up or something because I really can't see why I didn't write more about it once I'd added it to my shelves here.<br /><br /> It took me over. You know when you read a book and you start to feel caught up in its swell? Like the things the author or the character describes are somehow speaking <i> for </i> you in some ways that you can't quite understand, except that they are relating something personal unto them and yet they are also simultaneously describing the memories, dreams, reflections and sensations that you yourself have felt, running like telegrams under the thick, full folds of your unconscious? <br /><br /> Like the words are taken out of you, spoken for you, exhumed and exorcized in all their alien majesty back in black ink on flattened, whitened pieces of rippable pulp?<br /><br /> Forget categories, forget genres, forget classifications and taxonomies. This book is undoubtedly a fine example of 'queer discourse' (I'd seen it on more than a few curriculums to that effect and the person on whose shelf it rested was not really literary, probably a college text in a class she'd liked or something) and that is all perfectly well and good, but it transcends speaking from one narrowly defined social group and spoke robustly of its own humanity. <br /><br /> There's wisdom in this, I submit, and transcendence, and- perhaps- true enlightenment. Who's to say? Does it matter? Why should it? Why must it?<br /><br /> The fact that Winterson made her narrator genderless (a fact I remembered after all these years, excellently enough) speaks to that.<br /><br /> Look. Years before I read it something dreadful happened to somebody I love and though I loved them I couldn't love them, ultimately, enough. That has everything and nothing to do with what I want to write here but the plain fact is, whether Winterson knew it or not or even bothered to think about it or not or whether I'm putting words in her mouth by even saying this I knew EXACTLY what she meant by certain things she'd written herein. I'd lived it myself and this is precisely the way I'd have explained it, had I the courage and the brio Winterson needed and must have used to put this book together.<br /><br /> It's a little like Salinger's (or should I say Holden's) musing that a really good book is when you have the irrisitible urge to call the author up in the middle of the night and talk to them, be friendly with them; you feel like they are one of your own in some indescribable but irriducible way. I don't necessarily want or need to have Winterson over for tea or anything (though I'd like to) but it also feels like it wouldn't really matter. <br /><br /> Each sentence of this (novel) (memoir) (confession) rings with the truth that is ripped out of the core of things, the eddy of the actual, and each sentence is a hard diamond, glittering with the blood, the flesh, the yearning and the spirit. The deep heart's core. If those four words mean anything, they mean what they mean, and I'm glad that William Butler Yeats put them down and gave them some stately legitimacy. And for Winterson, too, of course, for having even more courage to write the book...<br /><br /> I didn't predict the hour, or the day, or the moment, or the person, or the author, but a very distinct and powerful moment in my personal history was connected by and to this book, before I'd even known of it at all it was there all the time, the perfect words to describe something millions know but I know in myself, by myself, and even then only from the outside, from the periphery, it didn't happen to me, you don't need to justify your suffering, it is there, it was there, there it will be...<br /><br /> Once there was a guy I worked with, didn't like him all that much, who sort of pronounced, unprompted, out of the blue, that I don't know 'real pain'. Well guess what, fucker, yeah I do. I *actually* do. <br /> <i> o yeah? </i> <br /> Yeah. <br /><i> what was it, then? </i> he snidely remarked.<br /> None of your goddamn business, I said. <br /> It wasn't. I don't have to justify that shit to you. Not to anyone, certainly, but especially not to your pompous, idiotic ass. You have my personal invitation to fuck right off into a barrel of snakes and broken glass. There was a pause. He knew. He backed down. We became friendlier later on, I decided I wasn't going to browbeat him and he didn't know what the hell he was talking about anyway. I prefer to make friends of enemies. He didn't know any better, and he was probably about twice my age. But I still hate him for that. And I should.<br /><br />...and the words were there, finally, unexpectedly, somewhere in the ether, written on the body.<br /><br /> I'm sorry, R. I love you, I loved you, but I am so deeply sorry.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10599111168969980417" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


