    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1929267447" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1929267447" />
    <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes"><img alt="aPriL does feral sometimes " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478243665p2/3409532.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1929267447?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="user" itemprop="url" name="aPriL does feral sometimes " href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes">aPriL does feral sometimes </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=literary">literary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1929267447" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10470244168173477207">&quot;Written on the Body&quot; is an extremely thoughtful, poetic and emotionally authentic novel about the fictional narrator&apos;s love affairs with women. I am amazed I somewhat liked it. Not only is it a novel of intense and analyzed descriptions of emotional and physical love in romantic sexual relationships, woman after woman (I HATE the Romance genre generally, with few exceptions), but the book struck me at first that it might be written in a type of literary writing which I usually find unappealing.</span>
  <span id="freeText10470244168173477207" style="display:none">"Written on the Body" is an extremely thoughtful, poetic and emotionally authentic novel about the fictional narrator's love affairs with women. I am amazed I somewhat liked it. Not only is it a novel of intense and analyzed descriptions of emotional and physical love in romantic sexual relationships, woman after woman (I HATE the Romance genre generally, with few exceptions), but the book struck me at first that it might be written in a type of literary writing which I usually find unappealing. The story actually ended up much more full of genuine life and realistic analysis, more like a journal of thoughtful musings and honest regrets over failed relationships, especially for the one that got away which really hurt. <br /><br />Many reviewers have commented on how the author, Jeanette Winterson, chose to keep the narrator's sexual gender a secret, but the novel has won both the Ferro-Grumley Award for Lesbian Fiction (1994) and the Lambda Literary Award for Lesbian Fiction (1994), probably because women's bodies are described in some detail and with a lot of passion by the nameless narrator. <br /><br />Usually authors writing in the approved Ivory-Tower, academic-scholar style feel to me like they are pandering to other academic scholars of literature instead of writing an authentic and illuminating book. However, I think 'Written on the Body' never drops into that overly intellectualized and contrived poetic cerebral agony manner of writing, which so often poisons intelligentsia-favored books for me (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/22929741.The_Argonauts" title="The Argonauts by Maggie Nelson" rel="nofollow noopener">The Argonauts</a> being such a one in the non-fiction category, and the fictional <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9717.The_Unbearable_Lightness_of_Being" title="The Unbearable Lightness of Being by Milan Kundera" rel="nofollow noopener">The Unbearable Lightness of Being</a> as another). Instead, Winterson's novel is beautifully written, with only rueful honesty or joy expressed by her nameless character about a number of love affairs. My problem with the book is entirely due to that I am not much of a fan of Romance literature, whether it be lowbrow or of the highest quality. I would have enjoyed the book more as a short story, I think.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10470244168173477207" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

